This picture of Russian prisoners in Poland was published in a September, 1915 magazine with this caption:
&quot;A Typical Loss of the Sort That Only Russia Can Stand
 There are 15.000 in this group of prisoners at Augustowo; but except for the equipment, the Slav forces would not miss them in the slightest.&quot;
<a href="http://blog.modernmechanix.com/among-the-russians/1/#mmGal" rel="nofollow">blog.modernmechanix.com/among-the-russians/1/#mmGal</a>
The same picture, in the Western Michigan University archve, is  from a printed page that says &quot;courtesy Colliers Magazine&quot;, is dated 1914 and captioned &quot;Despite early successes in invading East Prussia, the Germans, under General Paul von Hindenburg, bolstered the German defenses and soon drove the Russians back into Russian Poland. This photograph shows 15,000 Russian prisoners of war awaiting transportation to prison camps in Germany.&quot;
